segments.text: Have you been here 30 years?
This particular facility is 24 years old, I guess, right?
Something like that.
How long has the university been actively collecting special collections?
The material that we see in this library.
Okay, everything here can't be before 1890 because on February 14, 1890,
The library was then located in University College.
University College burned to the ground on February 14, 1890.
So everything since then, a few things were rescued and a few things were out on low.
Any really important things destroyed?
Well, our Audubon, for starters.
Do you have all five volumes of it?
We don't have it at all.
Did you have it?
Oh, yeah.
It was complete, yeah.
Sure.
So there's still one in Toronto.
The Metro has one, although they're threatening to sell it now.
They find that money's so seductive, don't they?
That's right.
especially public libraries.
That map they were going to sell up at Durham?
Oh, the map of Hereford.
Hereford, I'm sorry.
The map of Mundy.
I can tell you a long, scabrous story about that.
What happened finally?
Did they sell it?
Oh, no, they saved it.
They did save it.
Back in Hereford.
Good, yeah.
But the... I just found that on the internet the other night, just going through, believe it or not.
What happened here is that they start a campaign to replace the library.
So there's one little irony that I think you could say by, that was 1890, by 1900, within 10 years, and maybe even sooner, the collection actually was stronger than it had been before.
How did that happen?
That happened because of the response in particularly Britain and Germany, to some extent locally, and to some extent the United States, but there was a lot of stuff sent.
And places sent what they considered their duplicates.
So the Birmingham Public Library sent us Piranesi's Opera Barry in original boards.
This is 1890.
Probably about 1892 or so.
Just a hundred years or so.
And we were given extraordinary things.
But there was no Special Collections then.
There was an art cupboard.
The Special Collections Department was— The whole concept came in later than that, right?
Oh, sure.
In 1955 is when the Special Collections Department was founded, and they hired someone to run it.
Her name was Marian Brown, and I succeeded her.
So most of the stuff has really come in under your stewardship, I would say.
A lot of it has, yeah.
Have you had a focus, or is it just something that's defined by you?
We build on strength, but branch off into it.
In the great days of the 60s and early 70s, we would buy collections.
We'd buy, say, a Hobbes collection or a Darwin collection, then use that as a basis and build on it.
And you can't do that anymore?
Well, we don't very often buy collections.
We're sometimes given them.
quite often given them.
Is it because the money isn't available?
Well, I'll give you an example.
Now, I think this might even be part of that law.
In 1972, we bought eight books from J. Satan, and those eight books included 1478 Aristotle, the Hooke's Micrographia, 1645 or whatever it is,
The second edition of Boyle, Skeptical Chemist, books like that, eight of them.
The bill was $10,650, American, U.S., but in 1972, the Canadian dollar was worth more than the U.S.
dollar.
I remember American dealers were very happy to have Canadian checks.
And then larger.
I reckon now, I did a little calculation for this paper that I gave in Australia at ANU last November, that you could find all those books now.
You'd have to spend a week or two finding them, but you could find them.
They would now cost between 40 and 50 times what they cost there.
Eight books?
Eight books.
That just happens to be this one block that I
That was 1972.
Too bad you can't convert that into stocks.
That's right.
So you can see the stuff that was in the stocks, and it's been transferred, the stuff that's falling apart.
Have you ever gone out into general collections to identify things that more properly belong in special collections?
I used to do that all the time.
I used to go into both science and medicine and robots.
I still do it in robots a bit, but I just don't have time to do it very much.
You said building on strength.
Is that basically your general philosophy of collecting?
But if we get the opportunity... And the strengths being what, to recap them?

Well, there's lots of different strengths, but in a general sense, well, English literature post-restoration, although we do have a big Shakespeare collection, history of science, history of medicine, Canadiana, French 18th century...

Well, we do.

Not at all.

something in South Pacific Studies.

You don't feel that you have that kind of a restriction, right?
Is that your own philosophy or the philosophy of the university?
Well, they accept that.
I mean, I don't go and ask them.
If I went to the province and said, okay, in terms of building collections, are you absolutely comfortable with letting me define what gets acquired?
he would probably say, no, I'm not.
So don't invite them.
You don't ask.
You don't ask questions where you already know what the answers can be.
And, you know, don't fix it, right?
Can you think of any instances, other than that one you just mentioned, where you actually have acquired things with the expectation that it will be useful down the road.
Can you think of anything else?
Sure.
The newbie collections.
N-E-W-E-Y.
No reason you should ever have heard him of Tawley, but a 19th century, mid-19th century publisher.
His first name?
Thomas Cautley.
Okay.
Cautley, spelled C-A-U-T-L-E-Y.
He was the name known to people only because he published the first edition of The McDermott's of Ballyclaren, which is Tawley's first novel and a legendary rarity.
And he published the first edition of Wuthering Heights, also a legendary rarity, although you can see both of them at Princeton in original clock.
I got interested in him because he's dismissed normally in a line or two in 19th century publishing history as kind of a vanity publisher and little more than a cook.
Except he stayed in business for 40 years.
He published an immense variety of stuff.
So I decided it'd be interesting to put together an imprint collection for this guy.
So I did.
And the rationale being what?
Well, you could do research on 19th century publishing history from this collection.
There are no records of newbies anywhere that I know of.
You've got to extrapolate from the stuff.
So this is an archive waiting for a scholar, right?
That's right.
Well, I've done some work on it.
But that's okay to have things.
That's what attracts scholars, isn't it?
Here's the modern lit.

Go back to that Japanese thing you were talking about, and that started through a digital discussion.
Could you just kind of go over to me what we were talking about out there?
Well, the Japanese apparently have a system whereby individual faculty members are able to order books from their institutions.
Through the library.
We're talking about Japanese institutions.
Name a couple, for example.
Well, the University of Tokyo, which is the elite.
In Japan, there's 600 universities, and there's both public and private.
And unlike the United States, the prestigious ones, the most prestigious ones, are the public ones.
And Tokyo University is, you know, miles above everything else.
No kidding.
It's just an inversion of everything else.
To get into, if you can get into Tokyo, the University of Tokyo, or there are a couple of other examples, then you're guaranteed, or at least, now Japan's changing, but...
This certainly was true.
You were guaranteed middle management leading to upper management, cradle to grave, that whole Japanese system.
The competition to get in is why the teenage suicide rate in Japan is higher than anywhere in the world.
It's so hard to get in.
Contrast that with Meisei University.
which is owned by Mr. Kodama.
